# 1. AWS Setup:
#    a. Create an S3 bucket (e.g., `your-screenshot-bucket`) where screenshots will be stored.
#    b. Create an IAM role for your EC2 instance with permissions to:
#       - `s3:PutObject`
#       - `s3:GetObject` (if you need to read them back, though not directly used by this app)
#       - `s3:ListBucket` (optional, good for verification)
#    c. Launch an EC2 instance (e.g., t2.medium or larger as Chrome can be memory intensive).
#       - Attach the IAM role created in step b to your EC2 instance.
#       - Ensure port 5000 (or 80 if you configure Nginx/Apache) is open in the EC2 security group.

# 2. Local Development (optional):
#    a. Create a virtual environment: `python -m venv venv`
#    b. Activate it: `source venv/bin/activate` (Linux/macOS) or `venv\Scripts\activate` (Windows)
#    c. Install dependencies: `pip install -r requirements.txt`
#    d. Set environment variables (or create a .flaskenv file):
